-- 1. [Problem Restatement] Determine the digits A, B, C in the 9-digit decimal expansion ABCACCBAB of n = 3¹⁷ + 3¹⁰ and show that 100A + 10B + C = 129. 2. [Key Idea] Exploit three quick facts: (i) the last digit of n fixes B, (ii) the digit sum and the known value n ≡ 0 (mod 9) give A + B + C ≡ 0 (mod 3), (iii) the 11-divisibility rule applied to n + 1 (≡ 0 mod 11) yields B − A + C ≡ −1 (mod 11). These congruences, together with the parity/​distinctness conditions, pin down A, B, C uniquely. 3. [Proof] Direct computation (one-liner for completeness) 3¹⁷ = 129 140 163, 3¹⁰ = 59 049 n = 129 140 163 + 59 049 = 129 199 212 = 1 2 9 1 9 9 2 1 2 = ABCACCBAB. Hence (A,B,C) = (1,2,9) and 100A + 10B + C = 129. Elegant modular derivation (a) Unit digit. 3⁴ ≡ 1 (mod 10) ⇒ 3¹⁷ ≡ 3, 3¹⁰ ≡ 9, so n ≡ 3 + 9 ≡ 2 (mod 10). Therefore the last digit B = 2 (and B is indeed not divisible by 3). (b) Divisibility by 9. 3ᵏ ≡ 0 (mod 9) for k ≥ 2, so n ≡ 0 (mod 9). Since the digit sum of ABCACCBAB is 3(A + B + C), we have 3(A + B + C) ≡ 0 (mod 9) ⇒ A + B + C ≡ 0 (mod 3). (1) (c) Divisibility by 11. For a 9-digit number d₉…d₁, let S = d₁ − d₂ + d₃ − … + d₉. For ABCACCBAB, S = B − A + B − C + C − A + C − B + A = B − A + C. Given 11 | (n + 1), we have n ≡ −1 (mod 11), hence B − A + C ≡ −1 (mod 11). (2) (d) Search space. A, C odd (1,3,5,7,9), B = 2. Insert B into (1) and (2): (1) A + C + 2 ≡ 0 (mod 3) ⇒ A + C ≡ 1 (mod 3). (2) 2 − A + C ≡ −1 (mod 11) ⇒ −A + C ≡ −3 (mod 11) ⇒ C − A ≡ 8 (mod 11). Checking the five odd possibilities for A (1,3,5,7,9): A = 1 ⇒ C − 1 ≡ 8 (mod 11) ⇒ C ≡ 9, also 1 + 9 ≡ 1 (mod 3). Works. A = 3 ⇒ C ≡ 0 (impossible). A = 5 ⇒ C ≡ 2 (even). A = 7 ⇒ C ≡ 4 (even). A = 9 ⇒ C ≡ 6 (even). Thus the only admissible triple is (A,B,C) = (1,2,9). (e) Value required. 100A + 10B + C = 100·1 + 10·2 + 9 = 129. 4. [Conclusion] The unique digits satisfying all conditions are A = 1, B = 2, C = 9, hence 100A + 10B + C = 129.
